This executive summary is provided to comply with 40 CFR 68.155.



(a) The accidental release prevention and emergency response policies at the stationary source:

Air Liquide Electronics US LP, Dallas Chemical Center, 13546 North Central  Expressway, Dallas, TX 75243

(Air Liquide's Dallas Chemical Center) in order to prevent accidental releases operates using Standard Operating Procedures, Safety Information Reviews, Hazard Reviews, Operator and Contractor Training, Maintenance Procedures and Inspections, Compliance Audits, Management of Change Procedure, Pre-Startup Safety Review, Hot Work Permit Program, Incident Investigations, Emergency Action Plan, and ER Levels of Response. 









(b) The stationary source and regulated substances handled:

Air Liquide's Dallas Chemical Center facility stores three substances above the threshold quantities specified in 40 CFR 68: Chlorine Indoor Storage, Aqueous Hydrochloric Acid Indoor Storage and Ammonium Hydroxide Indoor Storage. 







(c) The general accidental release prevention program and chemical-specific prevention steps:

This facility complies with EPA's RMP Prevention Program 2 or 3 as applicable and all applicable state and local codes and regulations.



Some technological safeties and managerial practices in place that help to prevent or limit releases include:

--the use of management of change to ensure the covered process is not altered without a safety review;

--the storage of packages inside a building with liquid spill containment;

--the establishment of operator training and operating procedures (SOPs);

--the establishment of additional safety training;







(d) The five-year accident history;

Air Liquide's Dallas Chemical Center location has never had an accident involving Chlorine storage, Aqueous Hydrochloric Acid storage or Ammonium Hydroxide storage that caused deaths, injuries, property or environmental damage, evacuations, or sheltering in place.







